This should be general advice.
Was and passive voice, assuming one is writing in the past tense, are not sins in and of themselves. But they can lead to weaker overall writing.
Passive voice tends to require more words than active to describe the same action. The way I view it: is the subject dominant (has agency) over the action, or not? It's like a garnish.
On the other hand, using was instead of a more active verb may be the clearest choice on occasion.
